article.description:
Long since eliminated from the playoffs, the Los
Angeles Clippers and Denver Nuggets both approached the game Saturday
night with a simple goal: Don't quit on the season.
article.headline: Nuggets listless in dropping sixth game in a row
article.linkText: Clippers refuse to mail it in, blow out Nuggets
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Long since eliminated from the playoffs, the Los Angeles Clippers and Denver Nuggets both approached the game Saturday night with a simple goal: Don't quit on the season. Only Clippers coach Dennis Johnson was smiling afterward. Rookie Marko Jaric scored 17 points on 7-for-10 shooting, Andre Miller had 16 points and the Clippers routed the Nuggets 101-79. Corey Maggette added 14 points and 10 rebounds, and Lamar Odom had 13 points and 10 rebounds to help the Clippers snap a three-game losing streak. ''The thing you worry about when you have so few games left is you don't want the guys to quit on you,'' Johnson said. Since taking over as interim coach March 3, Johnson said his team has played hard in every game ''except maybe two.'' Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik agreed with Johnson's assessment. ''I probably shouldn't say this, but some guys were playing exceptionally hard tonight for the Clippers,'' he said. It was a different story for his own team -- the self-proclaimed ''hardest-working team in the NBA.'' ''Our effort tonight doesn't reflect how we've played throughout the season,'' Bzdelik said. ''Last night (in a 105-103 defeat against Sacramento), I thought we played our best game in a while. It's unacceptable for us to have such a turnaround.'' Los Angeles shot 46 percent and outrebounded Denver 60-50. The Nuggets, dropping their sixth consecutive game, shot 33.3 percent in each of the first three quarters and finished at 32.6 percent. Denver's Jeff Trepagnier had 10 of his career-high 15 points in the final quarter, and Juwan Howard and Shammond Williams each had 12 points. Los Angeles outshot Denver 51 percent to 33 percent in the first half en route to a 55-34 lead at intermission. Maggette had 11 points in the half and Miller 10. The Clippers led by as many as 28 points in the first half, and the short-handed Denver got no closer than 15 after that. Nuggets center Marcus Camby, who missed the game Tuesday because of the flu, sat out the second half after feeling ill. Howard played only five minutes of the second half after spraining his ankle. Nuggets rookie Nene Hilario did not play because of a lower-back strain. He was injured in the fourth quarter of the defeat Friday night in Sacramento. Jaric was 3-for-3 from 3-point range and scored 12 of his points in the fourth quarter. ''If somebody feels good for the night, we should let him play and get the ball in his hands,'' Jaric said. ''Tonight that was me.'' Los Angeles shot only 26 percent in the third quarter but still carried a 19-point lead into the final period. Baskets by Rodney White and Nikoloz Tskitishvili cut the deficit to 75-60 early in the fourth quarter, but the Clippers responded with a 15-3 run, including 3-pointers by Jaric and Miller. Miller scored eight points in the first quarter as the Clippers shot 52 percent to take a 30-16 lead. Maggette and Elton Brand opened the game with three-point plays, and Maggette's steal and slam dunk made it 14-5. Melvin Ely's baseline drive gave the Clippers a 27-13 lead, and Keyon Dooling hit a long 3-pointer at the buzzer after almost losing the ball out of bounds. The Clippers then scored the first 11 points of the second quarter while the Nuggets went 0-for-6 from the floor. Jaric and Dooling each had 3-pointers, and Ely's dunk produced a 41-16 lead. Brand put back his own missed shot, and the Clippers had their biggest lead of the game, 53-25 with 3:08 left. White's jumper capped a 9-0 Denver run, but Maggette hit a fastbreak layup to give Los Angeles a 55-34 halftime advantage. Denver failed to get off a shot in the last 21 seconds of the half. Game notes
Earlier Saturday, the Clippers placed guard Quentin Richardson on the injured list with a bruised left kneecap and activated forward Tremaine Fowlkes from the injured list (strained right shoulder). ... The Nuggets signed guard Jeff Trepagnier for the remainder of the season. ... Clippers forward Lamar Odom, who missed the game Friday night because of a sore left ankle, was back in the lineup. ... It was the fourth game in the Clippers' five-game road trip. ... The Clippers won for only the second time in the last 10 games in Denver. ... Denver's 63 defeats are the second-most in franchise history. They lost 71 in 1997-98.
